  "body": "A retired professor defies Florida's censorship laws; many faculty members in \nred states say they've avoided research topics; and more. \n\n\n\n ADVERTISEMENT \n \n<https://www.soka.edu/?advertising_Soka-University_academe-today_04-27-2026_970x250_inst&wlbelineID=2573910>\n\n\n\nTHE REVIEW | OPINION \n\nProfessors Are Too Old \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/professors-are-too-old> \n\nBy Samuel Moyn \n <https://www.chronicle.com/article/professors-are-too-old> \nThe academy’s gerontocracy problem is worse than anyone admits. \n\n\n\n ADVERTISEMENT \n <https://bit.ly/3NJkxL8?advertising_FAU_academe-today_04-27-2026_300x250 \nP1_inst&wlbelineID=3532049> \n\nSTANDING FIRM \n\nDefying His State’s Restrictions, a Retired Professor Teaches About Racism: \n‘History Has to Be Felt’ \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/history-has-to-be-felt> \n\nBy Katherine Mangan \n <https://www.chronicle.com/article/history-has-to-be-felt> \nAs censorship laws spread, FIU’s Michael Dunn has pitched a lone battle to \nfight back. \n\n\nBACKGROUNDER \n\nRacist Texts Shocked FIU. But the University Is Afraid to Talk About It. \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/with-banned-dei-safeguards-students-violent-racist-texts-roil-campus>\n\nBy Katherine Mangan \n \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/with-banned-dei-safeguards-students-violent-racist-texts-roil-campus>\nWith DEI banned, the campus is struggling to confront derogatory messages sent \nby young Republican student leaders. \n\n\n LIMITED-TIME OFFER: SUBSCRIBE FOR $1/WEEK \n\n\n <https://www.chronicle.com/subscribe?offer=ar4fmd1&oc=6H261WI101> \nEnjoying the newsletter? Subscribe today \n<https://www.chronicle.com/subscribe?offer=ar4fmd1&oc=6H261WI101> to try \nunlimited digital access starting at $1 a week. You’ll unlock indispensable \nreporting and insights, the subscriber-only Daily Briefing newsletter, and more.\n\n\nDATA \n\nNearly One-Third of Faculty in Red States Say They’ve Censored Their Research \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/nearly-one-third-of-faculty-in-red-states-say-theyve-censored-their-research>\n\nBy Sonel Cutler and Jacquelyn Elias \n \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/nearly-one-third-of-faculty-in-red-states-say-theyve-censored-their-research>\nA new survey of 4,000 academics looked at the effects of state laws barring \n“divisive concepts” and federal grant cuts. \n\n\nTHE REVIEW | OPINION \n\nNo, This Michigan Regent Wasn’t Defeated by Antisemitism  \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/no-this-michigan-regents-defeat-wasnt-about-antisemitism>\n\nBy Silke-Maria Weineck \n \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/no-this-michigan-regents-defeat-wasnt-about-antisemitism>\nJordan Acker’s failure was about real politics, not identity politics. \n\n\nDEVELOPING \n\nAnother Massachusetts College Closes \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/heres-the-latest-news-on-campus-finance> \n\nBy Chronicle Staff \n <https://www.chronicle.com/article/heres-the-latest-news-on-campus-finance> \nBudgets across the sector are under strain like never before. Here’s the \nlatest. \n\n\nUpcoming Professional Development Workshop  | May 2026\n\n\n \n<https://www.chronicle.com/professional-development/programs/the-chronicles-administrative-leadership-institute>\nThe Chronicle's Higher-Ed Leadership Institute \n<https://www.chronicle.com/professional-development/programs/the-chronicles-administrative-leadership-institute>\nHigher ed faces constant disruptions in today's turbulent landscape. The \nChronicle is hosting a virtual workshop series to help participants develop \ntheir own skills and practice complex leadership scenarios to be better \nprepared for their evolving challenges. Learn more and register today.  \n<https://www.chronicle.com/professional-development/programs/the-chronicles-administrative-leadership-institute>\n\n\n\nInsights and Events from The Chronicle\n\n\nVIRTUAL FORUM \n\nCommunicating with Students in the Age of AI \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/how-ai-can-improve-colleges-communications-with-students>\n \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/how-ai-can-improve-colleges-communications-with-students>\nREGISTER NOW: May 6, 2 p.m. ET | Generative artificial intelligence is a game \nchanger in how colleges communicate with students. It promises to offer 24/7 \nautomated responses, can sharpen marketing and student-recruitment messaging, \nand speak to students in a more personalized way. But to take advantage of the \ntechnology, institutions need strong guardrails and clear policies for using it.\nWith support from Zoom. Register now. \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/how-ai-can-improve-colleges-communications-with-students>\n\n\nVIRTUAL FORUM \n\nAffordable Training for Health Fields \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/affordable-training-for-health-fields>\n \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/affordable-training-for-health-fields>\nREGISTER NOW: May 14, 2 p.m. ET | The job market in health care is booming, \nand many colleges and universities are looking to train more health-care \nprofessionals to meet the demand. Hear how other institutions are creating \neffective and affordable training programs in our upcoming virtual forum.With \nsupport from Carolina Biological Supply. Register now. \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/affordable-training-for-health-fields>\n\n\nVIRTUAL FORUM \n\nNavigating College Mergers \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/navigating-college-mergers> \n <https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/navigating-college-mergers> \nREGISTER NOW: May 18, 2 p.m. ET | The number of mergers and acquisitions in \nhigher education has tripled over the past 20 years. With the growing \nenrollment and financial pressures institutions face today, even more colleges \nand universities are exploring this possibility. Hear about the future of \nmergers and partnerships in a panel discussion uncovering the hidden risks and \nsharing the lessons learned.With support from the University of Texas at San \nAntonio. Register Now \n<https://www.chronicle.com/events/virtual/navigating-college-mergers>. \n\n\n\n ADVERTISEMENT \n \n<https://bit.ly/4uETJwn?advertising_Texas-State_academe-today_04-27-2026_300x250 \nP2_inst&wlbelineID=4575502> \n\n\nThe Great Read\n\n\nTHE REVIEW | ARCHIVE \n\nHow Academic Corruption Works \n<https://www.chronicle.com/article/how-academic-corruption-works/> \n\nBy Lawrence Lessig \n <https://www.chronicle.com/article/how-academic-corruption-works/> \nIt’s not the morally lax scholar who’s most vulnerable. It’s the honest one. \n\n\n\nSPONSOR CONTENT  | Drexel University \n\n <https://sr.studiostack.com/c/link?l=2272853&s=2272847&wlbelineID=4410974> \nTransforming Higher Education for What's Next \n<https://sr.studiostack.com/c/link?l=2272853&s=2272847&wlbelineID=4410974> \n\nDrexel University President Antonio Merlo, PhD, reflects on how the University \nis strategically navigating this unique moment in higher education to secure an \neven brighter future for the institution and, above all, its students.\n\n\n FROM THE CHRONICLE STORE \n\n\n <https://store.chronicle.com/products/the-high-stakes-hunt-for-research-funds>\n The High-Stakes Hunt for Research Funds  \n<https://store.chronicle.com/products/the-high-stakes-hunt-for-research-funds> \n\nThe second Trump administration’s slashing of support for academic research \nhas left universities in disarray. Order this report \n<https://store.chronicle.com/products/the-high-stakes-hunt-for-research-funds> \nto explore how institutions are recalibrating their research agendas in an \nuncertain funding climate.\n\n\n FROM CHRONICLE CAREERS \n\n\n <https://jobs.chronicle.com/jobs/> \nJob Opportunities: Search thousands <https://jobs.chronicle.com/jobs/> of \nfaculty, administrative, and executive job openings andupload your resume \n<https://jobs.chronicle.com/profilecv> to be searchable by employers! \n\n\n FEATURED JOBS \n\n\n <https://www.chronicle.com/career-resources> \n Chronicle Careers <https://www.chronicle.com/career-resources/> provides \ninsights, tools, and advice to help you in career development, job seeking, and \nhiring.\n\n\n FEATURED EMPLOYERS \n\n \n<https://jobs.chronicle.com/employer/7009589/montgomery-county-community-college/?TrackID=230226&utm_source=widget&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=230226>\n \n<https://jobs.chronicle.com/employer/37275636/wayne-state-university/?TrackID=230226&utm_source=widget&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=230226>\n \n<https://jobs.chronicle.com/employer/7022199/rice-university/?TrackID=230226&utm_source=widget&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=230226>\n \n<https://jobs.chronicle.com/employer/37301857/hampton-university/?TrackID=230226&utm_source=widget&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=230226>\n <http://www.chronicle.com> \n\n© 2026 The Chronicle of Higher Education\n900 19th Street, N.W. 6th Floor, Washington, D.C. 20006 \n\n\n This email was sent to wschenk@gmail.com. \n\n <https://www.chronicle.com/account/newsletters>Read this newsletter on the web\n <http://www.chronicle.com/newsletter/academe-today/2026-04-27>.\n\nManage your newsletter preferences, stop receiving \n<https://links2.newsletter.chronicle.com/s/cu/xWNmh0u7MdOAndzWxA9_NJZQs7LqcfNfLFuzXve-NlQsqO4jUZaxi_F1r2fa6N7oNj-cg49SAp-hPcW1TBcQY8Da1FeL0MryFOcoM9JwPOXhsGFKFG_O2jsd7bcqEuZr6s5TaoxvkII15m3pZQtSmpadJeeBktS-2_pFyvzaJTIg_2Nv6iuxxcrLzjW9rzrbRm5HCcbYTKUOAWbTMCkc97miOopTFHiaxoxN/iFsdWEjcGmMd_AReF2oXv8nnB2Kar3y_/20>\n this email, orview <https://www.chronicle.com/page/privacy-policy/> our \nprivacy policy.",
